+		// hopssh patch 15 (2026-04-22): preferred_ranges-aware data-plane roaming.
+		//
+		// Without this, two paths to the same peer (LAN + NAT-PMP-reflected
+		// public, both viable via hairpin NAT) cause the hostmap to flip
+		// on every alternating packet, even with the 10s suppression window
+		// from patch 14 (the suppression only blocks re-flip to the
+		// IMMEDIATE-prior addr; with 2 alternating addrs both qualify as
+		// "not the prior" outside a tight window).
+		//
+		// Rules:
+		//   1. Current remote is in preferred_ranges, candidate is NOT
+		//      → ignore (we're on LAN, ignore public reflection).
+		//   2. Current remote is NOT in preferred_ranges, candidate IS
+		//      → roam immediately (LAN beats public; bypass time window).
+		//   3. Otherwise (both preferred, or both unpreferred)
+		//      → fall through to the time-window suppression below.
+		//
+		// Upstream Nebula already has this preference at handshake time
+		// (HostMap.SetRemoteIfPreferred / TryPromoteBest), but not in the
+		// data-plane roaming path — so once two paths are both reachable,
+		// the data plane keeps reverting to whatever sent the last packet.
